		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:>Notes for Monk top 10 issues list –<namespace prefix = o ns = "http://www.lithium.com/unique/URI"></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:>#1</SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:>Threads outline the problems <A href="http://pub147.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm1.showMessage?topicID=45252.topic" target=_blank><SPAN **SMURF**?COLOR: windowtext?><FONT color=#ffff00>http://pub147.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm1.showMessage?topicID=45252.topic</FONT></SPAN></A><FONT color=#ffff00> </FONT>(Thread reveals a pretty low "soft" cap on monk AC.) and here <A href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=monkbalance&amp;message.id=3747" target=_blank><SPAN **SMURF**?COLOR: windowtext?><FONT color=#ffff00>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=monkbalance&amp;message.id=3747</FONT></SPAN></A> (Discussion on mitigation) </SPAN><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><A href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=monkbalance&amp;message.id=4336" target=_blank><FONT color=#ffff00>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=monkbalance&amp;message.id=4336</FONT></A>&nbsp;(Brilliant Message on Mitigation - devs need to see this) </SPAN></P>
<UL type=disc 0in? **SMURF**?MARGIN-TOP:>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in justify; TEXT-ALIGN: 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list .5in? **SMURF**?MARGIN: lfo2; l2><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Equalize mitigation along all leather classes; the same armor should not be more efficient for druids and Beastlords.</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in justify; TEXT-ALIGN: 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list .5in? **SMURF**?MARGIN: lfo2; l2><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Our superior avoidance should be a class strength and an obvious advantage over Beastlords and druids, not a crux&nbsp;or an excuse to limit us in tank-ability.</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in justify; TEXT-ALIGN: 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list .5in? **SMURF**?MARGIN: lfo2; l2><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Silk classes are too close to leather classes in terms of mitigation and avoidance; they used to need any meat shield they can find, now they just require a good agro machine. This was a huge blow to the more limited classes like pure melees, of which the aftermath still echo's throughout definition.</FONT></SPAN></LI></UL>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>#2</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Monk relative DPS. Warriors, Rangers, Berserkers all parse very close to monks in DPS, whereas Rogues parse out well ahead of the rest of the pack. The relative gap is distorted. Here's a nice little reference thread: </FONT><A href="http://www.thesteelwarrior.org/forum/showthread.php?t=3803" target=_blank><SPAN **SMURF**?COLOR: windowtext?><FONT color=#cccccc>http://www.thesteelwarrior.org/forum/showthread.php?t=3803</FONT></SPAN></A></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Monks have only two roles. That of pulling and that of DPS if the DPS is relatively as lackluster as it measures out to be, then the class needs to be given some sort of power in other areas to compensate. Or the DPS gap between monks and their competitors needs to be widened a smidge.</FONT></SPAN></P>
<UL type=disc>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Special Attack DPS. Frenzy is pretty darn close to Flying Kick in terms of DPS. And yet Flying Kick has never been close to backstab in terms of DPS. </FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Monk naked fist damage. At this point in the game, you'd do well to put monk fist damage back to what it was on Planes of Power release ... 18 damage, 20 delay at level 65.</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Monk role as best DPS from "any angle" ... it's been suggested that the class could be given some sort of riposte immunity to allow them to attack raid level monsters from the frontal arc with little to zero penalty. For a raiding monk this would be a nice little boost to relative DPS (positioning would no longer be hampering DPS as a monk could get into&nbsp;a less crowded area of the monster, as well as help even out push) and could eventually give monks a more refined or specialized raid role (that of positioning). This concerns monk relative DPS specifically ... and Return Kick being as broken as it is, would mean that the ability, if put live to test, would turn out to be affected by the broken-ness of Return Kick and Double Riposte. So keep that in mind. I also bring it up because the description of Monks being the best DPS from "any angle" is a broken description. That's not the way EverQuest functions. DPS crowds the backs of monsters, due to monster defenses being lower from back there, and due to ripostes and other nasty things like Area Effects not affecting the back arc in many situations. The risks for standing anywhere but behind a monster is simply too high, so monks being the best DPS from angles besides the back, is simply a joke in terms of actual game play.</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>The difference between burst DPS and sustained DPS has shifted enormously. Before SOE took over from Verant, having burst DPS meant your sustained DPS was rather crappy, but the burst DPS was worth it and valuable. Today those burst DPS classes equal and surpass the sustained DPS classes in their sustained DPS. This did not only effect monks, but all classes who depend on close combat to deal damage.</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Seeing a monk deal 250 DPS and a wizard 350 DPS, sustained, might not seem like a terrible thing, wizards are meant to out damage monks, but what you see here is SUSTAINED DPS. We haven’t shown you the burst DPS of wizards yet...</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>In other words, there's no penalty for having huge burst DPS capabilities and monks along with other close combatant damage dealers are made redundant. This relativity is important and not class envy, it's actually vital for game balance that you equalize the efficiently of classes and put penalties in for huge benefits. One of these penalties date back from Verant times that burst classes deal crappy sustained DPS...</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; l0 mso-list: level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>I think the following statement holds true: "While monks get weapons in the bazaar of Luclin quality, their spell casting counterparts are getting spells and items which are equal in end PoP quality from the same bazaar in terms of DPS and efficiency."</FONT></SPAN></LI></UL>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>&nbsp;</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>&nbsp;</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>#3</FONT></SPAN></P>
<UL type=disc>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: lfo4; l1 .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>The Monk mitigation nerf was done, according to the patches (see one of my other posts for the long winded details of those patches) mostly due to the large amount of "All/All items" that proliferated EverQuest during Velious and Luclin. Well that itemization issue, to justify the nerf, needs to continue. Which means Monks need to have 125 AC BPs and 100 AC pants. Or else the monk mitigation nerf is simply stacking a penalty onto an itemization issue that doesn't exist. </FONT><FONT color=#ff0000>Dev notes - With the changes being considered to mitigation it is felt that this problem will be solved with the changes to mitigation not through items.</FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: l3 lfo3; .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Monk DPS through weapons is extremely poor in the areas of the very mudflated levels of 55 to non-raiding 65.&nbsp; The market is basically filled with things like War Marshall's Bladed Staff, Copper Hammer of Striking, Windblade, etc., etc., etc. Whereas monks are still scraping to nab Golden Wraps of the Compact/Waning Light Katar, or Staff of Flowing Water. For a class that is supposed to be DPS oriented, the gap at that "level" of the game is pretty small between them and the rest of the world. Rogues, at least, still have backstab to keep them ahead. </FONT><FONT color=#ff0000>(<SPAN FONT-FAMILY: red; COLOR: Roman?? New ?Times 12pt; **Oompa-Loompa**?FONT-SIZE:><SPAN FONT-FAMILY: Verdana? **Zowie**?COLOR: red;>This is something that will be&nbsp;added in future expansions)</SPAN></SPAN></FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: l3 lfo3; .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:></SPAN><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>It's extremely odd, we as a pure melee class have to "hope" to get druid or beastlord armor most of the time. Or hope to get beastlord weapons. Different classes rolling on items which are usefull for other classes is not the issue. So what is the issue? The armor and weapons we roll on are nearly ALWAYS designed for druids or Beastlords. There are no weapons or armor designed with mainly monks in mind.<SPAN yes? **SMURF**?mso-spacerun:>&nbsp; </SPAN>Monk only weapons or armor are extremely rare and all those weapons and armor we can use, are tailored&nbsp;for Beastlords or druids. Which means, lower AC then we actually require, Wisdom instead of Stamina, lower HPs because a hybrid/caster can use it etc. </FONT><FONT color=#ff0000>Dev notes&nbsp;- The same can be said for a warrior and a cleric sharing the same armor, or for a paladin and shadowknight sharing the same weapon. Classes share specific items between them, due to their armor class or similarity in weapon styles. Making sets of items for only monks would make it so that there is a lot of rotting items out there.&nbsp; In general the AC will be the same on a monk only item as it would be on a monk, beastlord, druid, shared item. The HPs stay relatively the same if it was a monk only item, or one that is shared with other classes. </FONT></SPAN></LI>
<LI class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; mso-list: level1 tab-stops: list **SMURF**?MARGIN: l3 lfo3; .5in;><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Combat mods (+kick, +block, Spell avoidance, DS avoidance&nbsp;etc)&nbsp;are also an issue of itemization, foci items are available at all stages in abundance, yet pure melees have to rely on getting to end PoP or end GoD zones for their foci items, which is not always possible. Well, which is USUALLY not possible...<SPAN yes? **SMURF**?mso-spacerun:>&nbsp; </SPAN>Current itemization is also a reason for the current DPS discrepancy amongst the classes (ie: Ranger Elemental Bows, FT items, Foci Items, lvl 65 spells available in the bazaar)</FONT></SPAN> <FONT color=#ff0000>Dev notes - The original design for focus effects was to make it so that casters have some type of gear to look forward to as they equipped themselves. Melees already had this through weapons and armor, since they get a much larger inherent gain from weaponry than a caster or priest does. A monk still gets a larger inherent gain from the various stats on a piece of armor compared to a druid. Combat mods were introduced as another “stick” for players at that level of play and while we will probably add small amounts of these combat mods to other areas of the game that isn’t Time+, it won’t be as common as focus effects.<SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:>&nbsp;</SPAN></FONT></LI></UL>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>#5</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Return Kick - AA. This AA has been broken since Luclin was launched. It and Double Riposte are pretty meaningless to begin with, due to the fact that only the main tank stands in front of most monsters these days, but even so, Return Kick could use some looking at.</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>#6</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P class=MsoNormal 0in auto? mso-margin-top-alt: mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; 0pt; **SMURF**?MARGIN:><SPAN Verdana? **SMURF**?FONT-FAMILY:><FONT color=#cccccc>Since monks became tied to the beastlord and druid classes in the great "clumping" of armor types, all the armor has ended up being the leather graphic (as there is no robe models for halflings or trolls and ogres ... and the monk specific armor set is obviously only on humans and iksars). There are no more robes. There's no more gi's. There's no more fist "wraps" or wrist "wraps" ... there's no more pants that look pants, just the little leather knickers. The class already has a hard enough time carving out its own niche and identity, but the graphic presentation of the class is so horrendously common, that we simply blend in, looking like a human druid most of the time. This is a far cry from the days of monks with slick tatooed chests or long flowing robes of the lost circle. Sleeper's Tomb should not be the last place a monk could ever loot a "robe."</FONT></SPAN></P>
<P>Message Edited by Ashlanne on <SPAN class=date_text>07-30-2004</SPAN> <SPAN class=time_text>05:16 PM</SPAN></P><p>Message Edited by Ashlanne on <span class=date_text>08-06-2004</span> <span class=time_text>04:35 PM</span>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
